<div class = "row">
<h3 style="text-align: left;">Workshop lessons</h3>
<hr>

<div class = "row">
<ul>
  <li><b><a href = "https://smbc-nzp.github.io/data_science_workshop/lessons/workflow_and_logic.html" target="_blank">Workshop introduction and logic</a></b>. The data science workflow, best practices, and a review and exploration of logic.
    <ul>
      <li><a href="code/workshop_logic_code.R" download>Startup code for lesson</a></li>
      <li><a href = "https://smbc-nzp.github.io/data_science_workshop/exercise_logic.html" target="_blank">Problem set</a></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><b><a href = "https://smbc-nzp.github.io/data_science_workshop/lessons/tidy_data.html" target="_blank">In pursuit of normal data (Codd’s rules & tidyr)</a></b>. The foundations and practice of generating tidy data.
    <ul>
      <li><a href="code/tidy_data_code.R" download>Startup code for lesson</a></li>
      <li><a href = "https://smbc-nzp.github.io/data_science_workshop/lessons/tidy_data_lf.html" target="_blank">Long form (not slides) version of lesson.</a></li>
    <li>Problem set: Use tidyverse and Codd's rules for normalizing data to tidy <a href="data/messy_weather.csv" download>this messy weather dataset</a>. Store your results as a list object. <i>Note: These data are real weather records from the NOAA, but they've been made untidy by me.</i></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Working with tidy data: Pipes, filters, and joins (magrittr, dplyr, stringr, lubridate). </li>
  <ul>
    <li><a href = "https://smbc-nzp.github.io/data_science_workshop/lessons/working_with_tidy_data.html" target="_blank">Presentation.</a></li>
    <li><a href = "https://smbc-nzp.github.io/data_science_workshop/lessons/working_with_tidy_data_skeleton.html" target="_blank">Long form version of lesson.</a></li>
    <li><a href="code/working_with_tidy_data.R" download>Startup code for lesson</a></li>
  </ul>
  <li>Functions and how to avoid them (dplyr)</li>
  <li>Data visualization (ggplot)</li>
  <li>For loops and how to avoid them (purrr)</li>
  <li>Applications: Introduction to geospatial analysis with R (sf)</li>
  <li>Introduction to data reporting (RMarkdown & Shiny)</li>
</ul>
</div>

